trans-unit.source: Builds a count table that can be used to create count-based features.
trans-unit.target: Builds a count table that can be used to create count-based features.

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Build Count Table</ui> module to analyze training data and create a <newTerm>count table</newTerm>, which contains the joint distribution of all feature columns given a specified label column.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Build Count Table</ui> module to analyze training data and create a <newTerm>count table</newTerm>, which contains the joint distribution of all feature columns given a specified label column.

trans-unit.source: You provide this table of counts as an input to the <link xlink:href="217741b5-730a-4c4b-839c-93c9cbb80ae7" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Count Featurizer</link> module, which uses the count-based information to create a set of features that is more compact than the original training data, but which captures all the most useful information.
trans-unit.target: You provide this table of counts as an input to the <link xlink:href="217741b5-730a-4c4b-839c-93c9cbb80ae7" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">Count Featurizer</link> module, which uses the count-based information to create a set of features that is more compact than the original training data, but which captures all the most useful information.

trans-unit.source: You can generate a new count table from a dataset each time you run your experiment, or you can write the table to blob storage or a Hive table, and then update or reuse the table in other experiments or with other data.
trans-unit.target: You can generate a new count table from a dataset each time you run your experiment, or you can write the table to blob storage or a Hive table, and then update or reuse the table in other experiments or with other data.

trans-unit.source: When new data becomes available to further enhance the model, you can create a new count table and merge it with previously created counts table to improve the joint distributions.
trans-unit.target: When new data becomes available to further enhance the model, you can create a new count table and merge it with previously created counts table to improve the joint distributions.

trans-unit.source: If you generate a set of counts that reflects the expected distribution of data in the real world domain, you can reuse that table when scoring new models, to ensure that features reflect the real world, rather than risk overfitting your model on a small and possibly skewed subset of data.

trans-unit.source: In statistical learning theory, a classification problem can be formulated as the problem of finding an estimate of a target function from labelled data drawn from an unknown fixed distribution.
trans-unit.target: In statistical learning theory, a classification problem can be formulated as the problem of finding an estimate of a target function from labelled data drawn from an unknown fixed distribution.

trans-unit.source: In fact, if there is a way to know the exact joint distribution of the features of the data and the label, you can readily estimate the target function, given a metric for evaluating the estimates.
trans-unit.target: In fact, if there is a way to know the exact joint distribution of the features of the data and the label, you can readily estimate the target function, given a metric for evaluating the estimates.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, if all combinations of all columns of the dataset are used to build the count table, the generated count table must completely describe the distribution of the label values over the training data.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, if all combinations of all columns of the dataset are used to build the count table, the generated count table must completely describe the distribution of the label values over the training data.

trans-unit.source: However, if there are <legacyItalic>N</legacyItalic> columns in the training data, then there are <legacyItalic>2^N</legacyItalic> choices of joint columns to count, which becomes an enormous number when <legacyItalic>N</legacyItalic> is large.
trans-unit.target: However, if there are <legacyItalic>N</legacyItalic> columns in the training data, then there are <legacyItalic>2^N</legacyItalic> choices of joint columns to count, which becomes an enormous number when <legacyItalic>N</legacyItalic> is large.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, in practice, you will typically choose a small subset of joint columns to build the count table, and use the count table to compute additional features, which can be used to train classifiers such as a decision tree or a neural network.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, in practice, you will typically choose a small subset of joint columns to build the count table, and use the count table to compute additional features, which can be used to train classifiers such as a decision tree or a neural network.
